<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-derivative"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivative</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Continuity says that nearby inputs produce nearby outputs. The
      derivative asks for something more precise: whether, near a point, the
      change in <m>f(x)</m> is approximately proportional to the change in
      <m>x</m>. This leads to the slope of the tangent line and, more
      importantly for analysis, to a first-order approximation of the
      function.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivative-at-a-point">
    <title>Derivative at a Point</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>, and let
      <m>c \in S</m> be a cluster point of <m>S</m>. We say that <m>f</m> is
      <term>differentiable at</term><idx>differentiable at a point</idx>
      <m>c</m> if the limit
      <me>\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}</me>
      exists. In that case, this limit is called the
      <term>derivative</term><idx>derivative</idx> of <m>f</m> at <m>c</m>
      and is denoted by
      <me>f'(c)=\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}.</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>S</m> is an interval and <m>c</m> is an endpoint of <m>S</m>,
      then the same definition is understood one-sidedly, using only points of
      <m>S</m> near <m>c</m>. Thus, on <m>[a,b]</m>, differentiability at
      <m>a</m> means the existence of the right-hand limit
      <me>\lim_{x\to a^+}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a},</me>
      and differentiability at <m>b</m> means the existence of the left-hand
      limit
      <me>\lim_{x\to b^-}\frac{f(x)-f(b)}{x-b}.</me>
      We say that <m>f</m> is <term>differentiable on</term><idx>differentiable on an interval</idx>
      an interval if it is differentiable at each point of the interval, with
      this endpoint convention when needed.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-derivative-of-square">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The function <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is differentiable on <m>\R</m>, and
          <m>f'(c)=2c</m> for every <m>c \in \R</m>. Indeed,
          <me>\frac{x^2-c^2}{x-c}=x+c \to 2c
            \quad\text{as } x\to c.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-absolute-value-not-differentiable">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The function <m>f(x)=|x|</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>.
          For <m>x \gt 0</m>,
          <m>(|x|-|0|)/(x-0)=1</m>, while for <m>x \lt 0</m>,
          <m>(|x|-|0|)/(x-0)=-1</m>. Since the left and right limits are
          different, the derivative at <m>0</m> does not exist.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-abs-not-differentiable">
          <caption>The graph of <m>|x|</m> has a corner at <m>0</m>, so there is no single tangent slope there.</caption>
          <image width="44%">
            <shortdescription>The graph of y equals absolute value of x has a V-shape with vertex at the origin.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=7cm,
  height=5.8cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-2.2, xmax=2.2,
  ymin=-0.4, ymax=2.4,
  xtick={-2,-1,0,1,2},
  ytick={0,1,2},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$}
]
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2:2, samples=100] {abs(x)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-caratheodory-criterion">
    <title>Carathéodory's Criterion</title>

    <p>
      The derivative is defined as a limit of quotients, but there is another
      viewpoint that is often more flexible: differentiability at <m>c</m>
      means that <m>f(x)-f(c)</m> factors as <m>x-c</m> times a function that
      is continuous at <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-caratheodory-criterion">
      <title>Carathéodory's Criterion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>, and let
          <m>c \in S</m> be a cluster point of <m>S</m>. Then <m>f</m> is
          differentiable at <m>c</m> if and only if there exists a function
          <m>\varphi \colon S \to \R</m>, continuous at <m>c</m>, such that
          <me>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi(x)(x-c)</me>
          for every <m>x \in S</m>. In that case,
          <me>\varphi(c)=f'(c).</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First suppose that <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>. Define
          <me>\varphi(x)=\begin{cases}
          \dfrac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} &amp; \text{if } x \neq c,\\
          f'(c) &amp; \text{if } x=c.
          \end{cases}</me>
          Then
          <m>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi(x)(x-c)</m> for every <m>x \in S</m>. Also,
          for <m>x \neq c</m> the definition of derivative gives
          <me>\varphi(x)=\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \to f'(c)=\varphi(c)
            \quad\text{as } x\to c,</me>
          so <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose there exists <m>\varphi \colon S \to \R</m>,
          continuous at <m>c</m>, such that
          <m>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi(x)(x-c)</m> for every <m>x \in S</m>. Then for
          <m>x \neq c</m> we have
          <me>\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}=\varphi(x).</me>
          Since <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, it follows that
          <me>\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}
            = \lim_{x\to c}\varphi(x)=\varphi(c).</me>
          Hence <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m> and
          <m>f'(c)=\varphi(c)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-differentiable-implies-continuous">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>, then <m>f</m> is
          continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>, there exists
          <m>\varphi \colon S \to \R</m>, continuous at <m>c</m>, such that
          <me>f(x)=f(c)+\varphi(x)(x-c).</me>
          The function <m>x \mapsto x-c</m> is continuous, so
          <m>x \mapsto \varphi(x)(x-c)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> by
          <xref ref="prop-algebra-of-continuous-functions"/>. Therefore
          <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-rules-of-differentiation">
    <title>Rules of Differentiation</title>

    <p>
      Carathéodory's criterion is especially effective for proving the
      differentiation rules. The point is that differentiability has been
      converted into a factorization statement, and such factorizations are
      easy to combine.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-derivative-sum-product-rules">
      <title>Sum and Product Rules</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f,g \colon S \to \R</m>, let
          <m>c \in S</m>, and let <m>\alpha \in \R</m>. If <m>f</m> and
          <m>g</m> are differentiable at <m>c</m>, then so are
          <m>\alpha f</m>, <m>f+g</m>, and <m>fg</m>. Moreover,
          <me>(\alpha f)'(c)=\alpha f'(c),</me>
          <me>(f+g)'(c)=f'(c)+g'(c),</me>
          and
          <me>(fg)'(c)=f'(c)g(c)+f(c)g'(c).</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>, there exist functions
          <m>\varphi_f,\varphi_g \colon S \to \R</m>, both continuous at
          <m>c</m>, such that
          <me>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi_f(x)(x-c)
            \quad\text{and}\quad
            g(x)-g(c)=\varphi_g(x)(x-c).</me>
          Also <m>\varphi_f(c)=f'(c)</m> and <m>\varphi_g(c)=g'(c)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Multiplying the first identity by <m>\alpha</m>, we get
          <me>(\alpha f)(x)-(\alpha f)(c)=\alpha\varphi_f(x)(x-c).</me>
          Since <m>\alpha\varphi_f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>,
          <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/> shows that <m>\alpha f</m>
          is differentiable at <m>c</m> and
          <m>(\alpha f)'(c)=\alpha\varphi_f(c)=\alpha f'(c)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Adding the two identities gives
          <me>(f+g)(x)-(f+g)(c)
            =(\varphi_f(x)+\varphi_g(x))(x-c).</me>
          Since <m>\varphi_f+\varphi_g</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>,
          <m>f+g</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>, and
          <me>(f+g)'(c)=\varphi_f(c)+\varphi_g(c)=f'(c)+g'(c).</me>
        </p>

        <p>
          For the product,
          <me>\begin{aligned}
          (fg)(x)-(fg)(c)
            &amp;= g(x)(f(x)-f(c)) + f(c)(g(x)-g(c)) \\
            &amp;= \bigl(g(x)\varphi_f(x)+f(c)\varphi_g(x)\bigr)(x-c).
          \end{aligned}</me>
          By <xref ref="prop-differentiable-implies-continuous"/>, <m>g</m>
          is continuous at <m>c</m>. Therefore
          <m>x \mapsto g(x)\varphi_f(x)+f(c)\varphi_g(x)</m> is continuous at
          <m>c</m>. Another application of
          <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/> yields the product rule:
          <me>(fg)'(c)
            = g(c)\varphi_f(c)+f(c)\varphi_g(c)
            = f'(c)g(c)+f(c)g'(c).</me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-chain-rule">
      <title>Chain Rule</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S,T \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to T</m>, and let
          <m>g \colon T \to \R</m>. If <m>f</m> is differentiable at
          <m>c \in S</m> and <m>g</m> is differentiable at <m>f(c)</m>, then
          <m>g \circ f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>, and
          <me>(g \circ f)'(c)=g'(f(c))f'(c).</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>, there exist functions
          <m>\varphi \colon S \to \R</m> and <m>\psi \colon T \to \R</m> such
          that <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>,
          <m>\psi</m> is continuous at <m>f(c)</m>, and
          <me>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi(x)(x-c)</me>
          for <m>x \in S</m>, while
          <me>g(u)-g(f(c))=\psi(u)(u-f(c))</me>
          for <m>u \in T</m>. Also
          <m>\varphi(c)=f'(c)</m> and <m>\psi(f(c))=g'(f(c))</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Substituting <m>u=f(x)</m> into the second identity gives
          <me>\begin{aligned}
          (g \circ f)(x)-(g \circ f)(c)
            &amp;= \psi(f(x))(f(x)-f(c)) \\
            &amp;= \psi(f(x))\varphi(x)(x-c).
          \end{aligned}</me>
          By <xref ref="prop-composition-preserves-continuity"/>,
          <m>\psi \circ f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, and hence so is
          <m>(\psi \circ f)\varphi</m>. Therefore
          <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/> shows that
          <m>g \circ f</m> is differentiable at <m>c</m>, with
          <me>(g \circ f)'(c)
            = \psi(f(c))\varphi(c)=g'(f(c))f'(c).</me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-differentiability-hypotheses-not-necessary">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The hypotheses in the sum, product, and chain rules are sufficient,
          but not necessary. For example:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Neither <m>f(x)=|x|</m> nor <m>g(x)=-|x|</m> is differentiable at
            <m>0</m>, but <m>f+g=0</m> is differentiable at <m>0</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The function <m>g(x)=|x|</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>,
            but <m>xg(x)=x|x|</m> is differentiable at <m>0</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The function <m>f(x)=|x|</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>,
            but if <m>h(x)=x^2</m>, then
            <m>(h \circ f)(x)=|x|^2=x^2</m> is differentiable at <m>0</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivatives-of-inverse-functions">
    <title>Derivatives of Inverse Functions</title>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>f</m> has an inverse function <m>f^{-1}</m>. Since
      <m>f^{-1}(f(x))=x</m>, the chain rule suggests that the derivative of
      the inverse should be the reciprocal of the derivative of <m>f</m>. The
      next proposition makes this precise.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-derivative-of-inverse-function">
      <title>Derivative of an Inverse Function</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I,J \subseteq \R</m> be intervals, let
          <m>f \colon I \to J</m> be a continuous bijection, and let
          <m>x_0 \in I</m>. Suppose that <m>f</m> is differentiable at
          <m>x_0</m> and that <m>f'(x_0)\neq 0</m>. If
          <m>g=f^{-1}\colon J \to I</m> and <m>y_0=f(x_0)</m>, then
          <m>g</m> is differentiable at <m>y_0</m>, and
          <me>g'(y_0)=\frac{1}{f'(x_0)}
            =\frac{1}{f'(g(y_0))}.</me>
        </p>

        <p>
          If, in addition, <m>f</m> is differentiable on <m>I</m> and
          <m>f'(x)\neq 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>, then <m>g</m> is
          differentiable on <m>J</m>, and
          <me>g'(y)=\frac{1}{f'(g(y))}
            \qquad \text{for every } y \in J.</me>
          If <m>f'</m> is also continuous on <m>I</m>, then <m>g'</m> is
          continuous on <m>J</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>g=f^{-1}</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-injective-continuous-on-interval-has-continuous-inverse"/>,
          the inverse <m>g</m> is continuous on <m>J</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>, there exists a
          function <m>\varphi \colon I \to \R</m>, continuous at <m>x_0</m>,
          such that
          <me>f(x)-f(x_0)=\varphi(x)(x-x_0)
            \qquad \text{for every } x \in I,</me>
          and <m>\varphi(x_0)=f'(x_0)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now let <m>y \in J</m>. Since <m>y=f(g(y))</m> and
          <m>y_0=f(x_0)=f(g(y_0))</m>, substituting <m>x=g(y)</m> gives
          <me>y-y_0=\varphi(g(y))(g(y)-g(y_0)).</me>
          Because <m>g</m> is continuous at <m>y_0</m> and
          <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>x_0=g(y_0)</m>, the function
          <m>y \mapsto \varphi(g(y))</m> is continuous at <m>y_0</m>. Also,
          <m>\varphi(g(y_0))=\varphi(x_0)=f'(x_0)\neq 0</m>, so
          <m>\psi(y)=1/\varphi(g(y))</m> is defined and continuous at
          <m>y_0</m>. Therefore
          <me>g(y)-g(y_0)=\psi(y)(y-y_0).</me>
          Another application of
          <xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/> shows that <m>g</m> is
          differentiable at <m>y_0</m> and that
          <me>g'(y_0)=\psi(y_0)=\frac{1}{\varphi(g(y_0))}
            =\frac{1}{\varphi(x_0)}=\frac{1}{f'(x_0)}.</me>
        </p>

        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is differentiable on <m>I</m> and <m>f'</m> never
          vanishes there, then the same argument applies at each point
          <m>x_0 \in I</m>. Hence <m>g</m> is differentiable on <m>J</m> and
          satisfies <m>g'(y)=1/f'(g(y))</m> for every <m>y \in J</m>. If
          <m>f'</m> is continuous on <m>I</m>, then <m>g</m> is continuous on
          <m>J</m>, so <m>f' \circ g</m> is continuous on <m>J</m> by
          <xref ref="prop-composition-preserves-continuity"/>. Since
          <m>f'(g(y))\neq 0</m> for every <m>y \in J</m>,
          <m>g'(y)=1/f'(g(y))</m> is continuous on <m>J</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      The proposition explains how to differentiate an inverse once we know
      that the inverse exists and is continuous. To guarantee this locally,
      it is enough to assume that the derivative is continuous near the point
      and does not vanish there.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-single-variable-inverse-function">
      <title>Single-Variable Inverse Function Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon (a,b) \to \R</m> be continuously differentiable, and
          let <m>x_0 \in (a,b)</m> satisfy <m>f'(x_0)\neq 0</m>. Then there
          exists an open interval <m>I \subseteq (a,b)</m> containing
          <m>x_0</m> such that the restriction <m>f|_I</m> is injective. If
          <m>J=f(I)</m> and <m>g=(f|_I)^{-1}\colon J \to I</m>, then
          <m>g</m> is continuously differentiable on <m>J</m> and
          <me>g'(y)=\frac{1}{f'(g(y))}
            \qquad \text{for every } y \in J.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>f'</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m> and
          <m>f'(x_0)\neq 0</m>, there exists an open interval
          <m>I \subseteq (a,b)</m> containing <m>x_0</m> such that either
          <m>f'(x)\gt 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m> or
          <m>f'(x)\lt 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-positive-derivative-implies-strictly-monotone"/>,
          the restriction <m>f|_I</m> is strictly monotone, hence injective.
        </p>

        <p>
          Because <m>f|_I</m> is continuous and <m>I</m> is an interval,
          <m>J=f(I)</m> is also an interval. Now apply
          <xref ref="prop-derivative-of-inverse-function"/> to the restriction
          <m>f|_I \colon I \to J</m>. Since <m>f'</m> is continuous on
          <m>I</m> and never vanishes on <m>I</m>, the inverse
          <m>g \colon J \to I</m> is continuously differentiable and satisfies
          <m>g'(y)=1/f'(g(y))</m> for all <m>y \in J</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-inverse-function-theorem-is-local">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The inverse function theorem is a local result. Let
          <m>f(x)=x^2</m> on <m>(-2,2)</m>, and take <m>x_0=1</m>. Then
          <m>f'(1)=2\neq 0</m>, so the theorem applies near <m>1</m>. For
          example, on <m>I=(0,2)</m> the function is injective, and its
          inverse is <m>g(y)=\sqrt{y}</m>. But <m>f</m> is not injective on
          all of <m>(-2,2)</m>, since <m>f(1)=f(-1)</m>. Thus the interval
          <m>I</m> in the theorem may have to be smaller than the original
          domain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-derivative-nonzero-needed-for-inverse">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The condition <m>f'(x_0)\neq 0</m> cannot be omitted. The function
          <m>f(x)=x^3</m> is a continuous bijection from <m>\R</m> onto
          <m>\R</m>, and it is differentiable everywhere. Its inverse is
          <m>g(y)=\sqrt[3]{y}</m>. However, <m>f'(0)=0</m>, and
          <m>g</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>, because
          <me>\frac{g(y)-g(0)}{y-0}=\frac{\sqrt[3]{y}}{y}
            =\frac{1}{y^{2/3}}</me>
          for <m>y\neq 0</m>, and this does not approach a finite limit as
          <m>y \to 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-inverse-function-theorem-needs-derivative-continuity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The continuity of <m>f'</m> near <m>x_0</m> is also important for
          the local existence of an inverse. Define
          <me>f(x)=\begin{cases}
            x+x^2\sin(1/x) &amp; \text{if } x\neq 0,\\
            0 &amp; \text{if } x=0.
          \end{cases}</me>
          Then <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>0</m> and
          <m>f'(0)=1</m>. For <m>x\neq 0</m>,
          <me>f'(x)=1+2x\sin(1/x)-\cos(1/x).</me>
          This derivative is not continuous at <m>0</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          In fact, <m>f</m> is not injective on any neighborhood of
          <m>0</m>. For <m>n \in \N</m>, let
          <me>a_n=\frac{1}{2\pi n+\frac{1}{2n}}
            \qquad \text{and} \qquad
            b_n=\frac{1}{2\pi n-\frac{1}{2n}}.</me>
          Then <m>0 \lt a_n \lt b_n</m> and <m>a_n,b_n \to 0</m>. A Taylor
          expansion of <m>\sin t</m> and <m>\cos t</m> at <m>t=0</m> shows
          that, for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>,
          <me>f'(a_n) \gt 0
            \qquad \text{and} \qquad
            f'(b_n) \lt 0.</me>
          Since <m>f'</m> is continuous on the closed interval
          <m>[a_n,b_n]</m>, the function <m>f</m> attains its maximum on that
          interval at some interior point. Therefore <m>f</m> takes some value
          twice on <m>[a_n,b_n]</m>. As these intervals shrink to <m>0</m>,
          no neighborhood of <m>0</m> can be one-to-one.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

  </subsection>
</section>
